'''Alexandre Tichonov''' is a former [[rugby union]] international who represented [[Soviet Union national rugby union team|the Soviet Union]] in the 1980s and early 1990s. He had the distinction of being asked to play for the [[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]] on their Easter 1990 tour of Wales and was one of two Soviet players, along with [[Igor Mironov]] to play in the [[Rest of Europe XV]] in 1990 against the [[Four Home Unions XV]] at [[Twickenham Stadium]].<ref name="Prog">''Four Home Nations v Rest of Europe - Official Programme'', page 23, 22 April 1990, Rugby Football Union</ref>

==Early life==
Alexandre Tichonov was born in around 1962 in modern day Russia. He studied at the [[Yuri Gagarin Academy]], [[Moscow]]. This academy, was named after the world's first astronaut, [[Yuri Gagarin]], who himself was reportedly a rugby enthusiast. The sports academy was a rich source of Soviet and now Russian internationals.<ref name="Tel">[http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/rugbyunion/international/ireland/3034747/Irish-try-the-craic-in-Krasnoyarsk.html Brendan Gallagher, ''Irish try the craic in Krasnoyarsk'', The Telegraph, Published: 12:01AM BST 19 Sep 2002]</ref>

==Rugby union career==
Tichonov played his club rugby for Yuri Gagarin Academy. He played in the final days of the old Soviet Union and it was a golden period for Soviet rugby. Four times in succession, from 1986 to 1989, the team was runners-up in the FIRA tournament behind the first tier team, France. This tournament including both  Romania and Italy, the latter of whom has since joined the first tier teams of Europe to play in the [[Six Nations Championship]]. The team he played in staged tours to England and New Zealand. Playing at No.8 or flanker, Tichonov  standing at 6&nbsp;ft. 4ins and weighing 15stones and 12&nbsp;lbs, was described as athletic and close to world-class.<ref name="Tel"/>

He had the distinction of being asked to play for the [[Barbarian F.C.|Barbarians]] on their Easter 1990 tour of Wales.<ref name="Prog2">''Four Home Nations v Rest of Europe - Official Programme'', page 27, 22 April 1990, Rugby Football Union</ref> This was after an international schedule from November 1989 during which he had played in the United Kingdom, Australia and Hong Kong. He was one of two Soviet players, along with [[Igor Mironov]] to play in 1990 [[The Skilball Trophy|Skilball Trophy]] match for [[Rest of Europe XV]] against the [[Four Home Unions XV]] at [[Twickenham Stadium]] to raise money for the rebuilding of Romania following the overthrow of [[Nicolae Ceau<U+015F>escu]] in December 1989.<ref name="Prog"/> The mid-season Russian break had afforded him the time to do this, and he returned to Moscow to complete the season for his club side.

